      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Introduction</h3>In the previous chapter, we studied how the development of counting systems has helped shape our daily lives. In this chapter, we will explore another fundamental aspect of both life and science: the act of comparison.</p><p>Often, we classify things as equal because they appear similar, but in reality, they are quite different. Conversely, we may label some animals as distinct, even though they are closely related. In this chapter, we begin to delve into these contradictions and explore the nature of comparison.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_initial",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>What Does It Mean to Be Equal?</h3>Before we begin comparing, it is important to define the concept of equality. For this study, we highlight the following definition of the word equal from the Britannica Dictionary (<htcite0>):</p><p><ul class=\"citation\"> <li>\"<i>B1. the same in amount, number, or size.</i>\"</li></ul></p><p>With this definition in mind, let us examine <b>Chart 1</b>:</p><p><div class=\"htTwoGeometricalRectangle\"> <div class=\"htFirstGeometrical\"><div class=\"htCircle\" style=\"height: 12vh; width: 12vh;\"></div></div> <div class=\"htSecondGeometrical\"><div class=\"htCircle\" style=\"height: 12vh; width: 12vh;\"></div></div> </div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 1</b>: Two identical circles.</p><p>In <b>Chart 1</b>, we see two circles that perfectly match the definition of equal—they are identical in every characteristic. Now, let's compare this with <b>Chart 2</b>:</p><p><div class=\"htTwoGeometricalRectangle\"> <div class=\"htFirstGeometrical\"><div class=\"htCircle\" style=\"height: 12vh; width: 12vh;\"></div></div> <div class=\"htSecondGeometrical\"><div class=\"htCircle\" style=\"height: 12vh; width: 12vh; background-color: blue;\"></div></div> </div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 2</b>: Two similar circles, but with different colors.</p><p>In <b>Chart 2</b>, the two circles are identical in every way except for their color. Thus, while they are similar (<htcite1>), they are not exactly the same.</p><p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\">?</div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: On Groups</b><br /><br />Does changing the color of an object change its type?</div></div></center></p><p>To answer this question, we first need to define what a circle is. According to Eric W. Weisstein definition (<htcite2>):</p><p><div class=\"desc\"><div class=\"circle2\" style=\"width:12vh;height:12vh;display: flex;align-items: center;justify-content: center;\"><div class=\"circle\" style=\"width:1vh;height:1vh;background-color:black\"></div></div></div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 3</b>: A circle used in the mathematical definition.</p><p><ul class=\"citation\"> <li>\"<i>A circle is the set of points in a plane that are equidistant from a given central point.</i>\"</li></ul></p><p>Since the definition of a circle does not include color as an essential characteristic, the fact that the circles in <b>Chart 2</b> have different colors does not alter their geometric properties. They remain circles.</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "425c72c4-6286-44cf-80e9-d9b21d0735ea",
                     "text": "The Britannica Dictionary",
