      {
         "id": "SECTION_history",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Comparisons in History</h3>Comparisons play a fundamental role in the sciences, helping us better understand nature. In history, comparing objects allows us to identify their origins and trace connections between different cultures.</p><p><h4>Mesoamerica</h4>Let’s examine a practical example. The metates shown in <b>Figure 1</b> are of different colors and were exhibited in separate museums during different visits. However, because they share similar characteristics and date from the same period, it is possible to determine that both originated in Costa Rica, where these pieces were traditionally made (<htcite0>).</p><p><table class=\"book_navigation\"><tr><td>Costa Rica</td><td>El Salvador</td></tr><tr><td><img  id=\"img0\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img0', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td><td><img  id=\"img1\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img1', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" class=\"desc\"><b>Figure 1</b>: Metates in the shape of a jaguar. On the left, a photograph taken on <htdate0></span>, during a visit to the Museo de Antropología in San José, Costa Rica. On the right, a photograph taken on <htdate1></span>, during a visit to the Museo de Antropología in San Salvador, El Salvador.</td></tr></table></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3fb52297-2d42-46f2-8ef1-b8a2c8f4052a",
                     "text": "HOOPES, J. W.",
                     "page": "pp. 459",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "09",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "17"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "7",
                     "day": "25"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "In these figures, it is showing a table in jaguar shape. The back of the jaguar is plane, allowing the functional usage of the surface.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<h4>Pyramids</h4>When analyzing historical structures, we should not only consider their shapes and visible characteristics. Often, different civilizations constructed similar-looking structures that served entirely different purposes. A clear example is pyramidal structures, which can be found in various regions of the world, built by cultures with no contact with each other (<htcite0>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7561d65f-e3f0-4593-8bba-2c76cda1a32f",
                     "text": "Mark, J. J.",
                     "page": "Pyramid",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2009",
                        "month": "09",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\">?</div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: On Pyramids</b><br /><br />What is a pyramid?</div></div></center></p><p>One reason people may believe that pyramids across the world have a common origin is due to a misunderstanding of what a pyramid truly is. To clarify, let's simplify the definition proposed by Eric W. Weisstein (<htcite0>) while maintaining its essence:</p><p><table class=\"book_navigation\"><tr><td>Quadrangular Pyramid</td><td>Pentagonal Pyramid</td></tr><tr><td><img id=\"img2\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img2', '0%')\"  class=\"imgcenter\"/></td><td><img id=\"img3\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img3', '0%')\"  class=\"imgcenter\"/></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" class=\"desc\"><b>Figure 2</b>: Examples of pyramids illustrating the mathematical definition.</td></tr></table></p><p><ul class=\"citation\"> <li>\"<i>A pyramid is a geometric figure with a closed base and triangular faces that converge at a single point at the top, known as the apex.</i>\"</li></ul></p><p>From this definition, we can explore the different pyramids built around the world.</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1aae32d7-8b8a-49d9-b136-f859e24a53e6",
                     "text": "Weisstein",
                     "page": "Eric W. Pyramid",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "09",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><h4>Egypt</h4>In Egypt, the most well-known pyramids, located on the Giza Plateau, were built during the Fourth Dynasty (<htcite0> ; <htcite1>). However, before these iconic structures were constructed, the Egyptians went through a long process of experimentation (<htcite2>):</p><p><ul><li><b>First and Second Dynasties</b>: The process began with the construction of burial tombs in the region known as Abydos (<htcite3>, pp. 48 - 58).</li><li><b>Third Dynasty</b>: This era saw the building of step pyramids (<htcite4> ; <htcite5> ; <htcite6>).</li><li><b>Fourth Dynasty</b>: The Egyptians constructed true pyramids, but these were not their first attempts. The method was gradually improved through structures like the Bent Pyramid (<htcite7>) and the Red Pyramid, eventually culminating in the Pyramids of Giza (<htcite8>).</li></ul></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "920578b1-b37d-4c0d-8aef-58e24136bdca",
                     "text": "Britannica, T. Editors of Encyclopaedia",
