            {
               "text": "<p>Despite differences in their forms, Egyptian pyramids share two key characteristics: they were built along a branch of the Nile (Ahramat) (<htcite0>) and were used as tombs (<htcite1>; <htcite2>).</p><p><h4>Mesoamerica</h4>When observing pyramidal structures in Mesoamerica, we notice significant differences. These structures often feature ornamentation, staircases, and windows, moving them away from the strict mathematical definition of a pyramid. A prime example is the \"sacred mountain\" in the city of Xunantunich, Belize, as shown in <b>Figure 3</b>:</p><p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"img4\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img4', '0%')\"  class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 3</b>: Sacred mountain at Xunantunich, Belize. Photograph taken on <htdate2></span>, during a visit to the archaeological site.</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "56225a39-761d-49c2-9caa-ed02b33926c2",
                     "text": "Ghoneim, E., Ralph, T.J., Onstine, S. et al",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "09",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e8ccb530-ef38-42ef-aaaf-5257f3d667e4",
