      {
         "id": "SECTION_language",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Equals Forever</h3>We've already introduced the concept of equality in images and buildings, but there's another type of equality that relates to the examples we've seen and can create discomfort for some people: mathematical equality.</p><p>In mathematics, we use the symbol \"=\" to indicate that two values or entities are equivalent. The purpose of using mathematics is to convey information in a simpler and more precise way than a descriptive text might. Let's take an example by first describing the metates in <b>Figure 1</b> before expressing the same information mathematically:</p><p><ul class=\"citation\"> <li>\"<i>The metates displayed in both museums share exactly the same fundamental characteristics: they have the shape of a jaguar, identical dimensions, and therefore the same weight. Thus, we can say that the metate from Costa Rica, labeled CRM, and the metate from El Salvador, labeled ESM, are both examples of the same type of jaguar-shaped metate, labeled JM.</i>\"</li></ul></p><p>This entire paragraph can be summarized mathematically as:</p><p><ul class=\"citation\"><li>ESM = CRM = JM</li></ul></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Equation 1</b>: Relationship between the metates.</p><p>It’s clear that reading only <b>Equation 1</b> without prior explanation may not provide a full understanding. However, once we know the meaning of the names and acronyms, we can express this information in a much more concise way through mathematics.</p><p>When we establish a mathematical equality, it’s essential to remember that once defined, it must remain consistent. In other words, if we change one side of the equation, we must make a corresponding change to the other side to maintain balance. Let's do a simple exercise with numbers and our hands, using arrows to illustrate:</p><p><table id=\"yupana0\" class=\"tawapukllay\"><tr><th colspan=\"4\"><i>Equation</i></th><th>Left Hand</th><th>Right Hand</th><th>Arrows</th></tr> <tr id=\"tf1\"><td id=\"tc1f1\"><span class=\"text_to_paint\" id=\"leftnum\">0</span></td></td> <td id=\"tc2f1\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"text_to_paint\">=</span></td> <td id=\"tc4f1\"><span class=\"text_to_paint\" id=\"rightnum\">0</span></td><td id=\"tc5f1\" style=\"background-color:white;\"><img id=\"leftHandImg\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('leftHandImg', '0%')\"  /></td><td id=\"tc6f1\"><img id=\"rightHandImg\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('rightHandImg', '0%')\"  /></td><td id=\"tc7f1\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-up upArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeUp0\"></i>  <i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-down downArrowWithFA\"style=\"font-size:4em;color:#00f;\" id=\"traineeDown0\"></td></tr></table><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Maintaining equality.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_conclusion",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Conclusion</h3>In this text, we began exploring the concept of equality in different ways. We observed that there are situations where objects are exactly the same, while in other cases, small variations do not make them fundamentally different. Additionally, we saw that objects with similar appearances, such as pyramidal structures, can have distinct meanings and uses when analyzed within the context of the civilizations that created them.</p><p>In the next text, we will delve deeper into the different levels of equality and how these concepts are applied across various fields of knowledge.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
